\lim{a_n}=L
n
\{a_n\}
\displaystyle\lim_{n \to\infty}{a_n}=L \Leftrightarrow{\forall{\epsilon}>0}
\exists{N}\in{\mathbb{N}}
\forall{n}>N \left |{a_n-L}\right |< \epsilon
m>N,\left |{a_m-L}\right |=\left |{L-a_m}\right |< \epsilon
 \textbf{Solution} 
\epsilon > 0 
 \lim a_n = L 
N_1, N_2 
 |a_n - L | < \epsilon/2 \; \; \; \text{for all} \;\;n \geq N_1 
 |a_m - L | < \epsilon/2 \; \; \; \text{for all} \;\;m \geq N_2 
N_1
N_2
N = \max\{N_1, N_2 \} 
 \therefore |a_n - a_m| = |a_n - L + L - a_m| \leq  |a_n - L| + |L - a_m| < \epsilon/2 + \epsilon/2 = \epsilon 
m, n \geq N
